  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Sudan: Investigating human rights violations by security forces</narrative>
  </title>
  <description type="1">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">As a result of nationwide demonstrations in Sudan that started by mid-December 2018 and requested former President Omar al-Bashir to step down, activities in Sudan were put on hold in 2019. In 2020, work with our local partner was to restart following a field visit to Sudan in the first quarter of 2020, allowing for initial discussions on the contours of the follow-up project. Yet, due to covid-19, plans were further delayed.</narrative>
  </description>
  <description type="4">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Political unrest in Sudan in December 2018, brought Sudanese people to the streets to express their anger over the rising cost of living and erosion of political freedoms. The protests led to a military coup in April which overthrew the National Congress Party (NCP) government, and President al-Bashir and other senior party leaders were arrested. On 17 August 2019, after lengthy negotiations between the military and a coalition of opposition groups, the Constitutional Declaration was signed. It contained a new Bill of Rights strengthening the protection of human rights. On 21 August, the Transitional Military Council (TMC) was dissolved and a new Sovereign Council and Prime Minister were appointed. A new cabinet was formed in September 2019. 

Despite these positive developments, the situation in Sudan remains highly volatile, as the country is marked by a deepening economic crisis. In addition, it cannot be ignored that the demonstrations were met with excessive use of force and unlawful killings by Sudanese security forces against peaceful protesters . Security forces used live ammunition against demonstrators, beat them on the streets and in hospitals and arbitrarily detained thousands who faced torture and other ill-treatment in detention. These violations mainly remain under investigation.</narrative>
  </description>
